WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.633
(Sound of Air Force 1 taxiing)

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:17.367
♪♪(Guitar strumming)♪♪

00:00:17.367 --> 00:00:20.066
Secretary Salazar:
President Obama and
his family decided as

00:00:20.066 --> 00:00:22.667
part of their summer they would
actually visit national parks

00:00:22.667 --> 00:00:25.800
because it is a
unifying American idea,

00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:29.100
fundamentally democratic, and
very much a part of our future.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:31.800
President Obama:
I have great
memories of being here.

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:36.834
My grandma, my mom, and my
sister, who is with us today,

00:00:36.834 --> 00:00:39.467
she was two at the time, and
we traveled throughout the

00:00:39.467 --> 00:00:42.133
country the entire summer.

00:00:42.133 --> 00:00:45.000
Our last stop was
our favorite stop.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.533
Ken Burns:
The national parks, I think,
are studies in leadership.

00:00:48.533 --> 00:00:52.800
How presidents have related to
the national parks have been in

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:56.767
some ways defining aspects of
their larger leadership quality.

00:00:56.767 --> 00:01:00.100
♪♪

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:04.500
Park Ranger:
Well, I think it's always
special when a president visits anywhere.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:07.934
Chester A. Arthur was the first
to visit Yellowstone in 1883.

00:01:07.934 --> 00:01:12.500
President Theodore Roosevelt,
Roosevelt came in 1903.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:17.100
Then in 1923 Warren Harding.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:22.767
In 1927 silent Calvin
Coolidge visited us.

00:01:22.767 --> 00:01:29.800
Then in 1937 FDR, President
Franklin Delano Roosevelt, came.

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:30.100
♪♪

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:32.834
Newscaster:
President Franklin D. Roosevelt, swinging through the west on a

00:01:32.834 --> 00:01:36.633
campaign tour, took time out for a
visit to Yellowstone National Park.

00:01:36.633 --> 00:01:39.934
An exponent of conservation,
Mr. Roosevelt backed many

00:01:39.934 --> 00:01:44.333
measures aimed at enlarging our national
forests and preserving wildlife.

00:01:44.333 --> 00:01:49.967
This was a moment of relaxation
amid the scenes he loved.

00:01:49.967 --> 00:01:52.400
Former President Ford:
This is a moment that I
have been looking forward

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:54.367
to for a long, long time.

00:01:54.367 --> 00:01:59.800
To return to Yellowstone where
I spent one of the greatest

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:03.000
summers of my life.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.066
Park Ranger:
Gerald Ford was an interesting
example of a President,

00:02:06.066 --> 00:02:09.467
because he had been a
park ranger in Yellowstone.

00:02:09.467 --> 00:02:14.166
Then after Ford, Jimmy Carter
came to Yellowstone and was

00:02:14.166 --> 00:02:17.834
again fishing, was
his primary focus.

00:02:17.834 --> 00:02:22.200
After Carter, George Herbert
Walker Bush who came to

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:25.200
Yellowstone in 1989.

00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:28.133
Bill Clinton was here twice.

00:02:28.133 --> 00:02:29.233
Former President Clinton:
Yellowstone is the symbol of our

00:02:29.233 --> 00:02:32.400
national parks because it's the
oldest one and the first one in

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.900
the history of the world.

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:38.166
Park Ranger:
And then after Bill
Clinton, of course, we had

00:02:38.166 --> 00:02:41.166
President Barack Obama.

00:02:41.166 --> 00:02:42.867
President Obama: You know, the
thing I remember most was,

00:02:42.867 --> 00:02:47.367
you know, driving by and
seeing -- it was elk.

00:02:47.367 --> 00:02:50.567
And I remember bison.

00:02:50.567 --> 00:02:55.200
In fact, I ran up close to a
bison and took some pictures of him.

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:56.100
(laughter)

00:02:56.100 --> 00:03:03.567
Park Ranger:
It's never a good idea
to approach bison closely.

00:03:03.567 --> 00:03:06.166
Park Ranger:
The Recovery Act has
been a real boon for us.

00:03:06.166 --> 00:03:08.400
It's been welcome dollars.

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.667
The great thing about the way
the National Park Service in

00:03:10.667 --> 00:03:13.066
Yellowstone approached
the Recovery Act,

00:03:13.066 --> 00:03:16.800
the funding with that, was we
wind up a variety of projects

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:19.300
that we already had in the queue
of things that we wanted to do.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:20.333
♪♪

00:03:20.333 --> 00:03:22.600
President Obama:
The notion that collectively
we come together and we say,

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:25.367
you know, we're going
to preserve some things

00:03:25.367 --> 00:03:29.700
that last beyond our
individual lives,

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:32.133
that we're going
to pass that on.

00:03:32.133 --> 00:03:33.834
And we have to do it together.

00:03:33.834 --> 00:03:38.000
You know, that's part of what is
hopefully best about our government.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.400
And so every once in a while we
need the ability to step back

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:49.066
from our personal wants and
project something finer and

00:03:49.066 --> 00:03:51.734
better for future generations.

00:03:51.734 --> 00:03:53.967
That's what the park
district is all about.

00:03:53.967 --> 00:04:01.100
♪♪

